orms of the local equivalents of the personal name   Nicholas  . Compare   Clauson  ."]},{"name":"Claxon","meanings":["English (Essex): variant of   Claxton  . This name is absent from the medieval record, and is therefore unlikely to be a patronymic from the medieval personal name <i>Clak</i> + <i>son</i>."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":59,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Claxton was born in 1490, in Norfolk, England. He married Isabel before 1510, in Little Melton, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1557, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1490–1557":"1490–1557","1490–1560":"1490–1560","1510–1562":"1510–1562","1557":"1557","before 1510":"enne 1510","1510":"1510","1562":"1562","about 1510":"umbes 1510","1560":"1560","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","